🚀 Build Animated Websites
with Claude Code
The complete step-by-step setup guide


Websites with professional animations that used to cost ₹3–4 lakhs can now be built using Claude Code + a few free tools. Follow these four steps and you're ready to generate production-quality animated UIs through natural language.

💡 What you need before starting: A Claude Pro or Max account ($20/month at claude.ai) and a basic terminal on your computer.




STEP 1  Install Claude Code


What is Claude Code?
Claude Code is Anthropic's AI coding agent that runs directly in your terminal. It reads your codebase, writes files, and handles complex multi-file edits — all through plain English instructions.

Installation
Run the command below in your terminal based on your operating system:

Mac / Linux / WSL:
curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | bash

Windows (PowerShell):
irm https://claude.ai/install.ps1 | iex

Verify Installation
claude --version

First-time Setup
Run claude in your terminal. It will open your browser to log in with your Anthropic account.

⚠️  You need a Claude Pro ($20/month) or Max plan. The free Claude.ai plan does NOT include Claude Code access.


🔗 Official docs: https://claude.ai



STEP 2  Install Framer Motion


What is Framer Motion?
Framer Motion is the industry-standard animation library for React. It handles all the scroll-triggered animations, page transitions, hover effects, and micro-interactions that make websites feel premium.

Option A — Create a new React project (recommended)
npx create-react-app my-website
cd my-website
npm install framer-motion

Option B — Add to an existing project
npm install framer-motion

Verify it works
npm start

💡 Framer Motion works with React, Next.js, and Remix. If you're building with Next.js, the same install command applies.


🔗 Framer Motion docs: https://www.framer.com/motion



STEP 3  Download the UI/UX Pro Skills Package


What is the Skills Package?
This is a custom CLAUDE.md configuration file that gives Claude Code deep UI/UX context at the start of every session. Without it, Claude generates average-looking UI. With it, Claude follows design principles, component structure, and your code style automatically — consistently producing better output.

How to set it up
Go to the GitHub repository link shared in the reel/DM
Download or clone the repository to your computer
Copy the CLAUDE.md file into the root folder of your project

# Example
cp CLAUDE.md /your-project-folder/CLAUDE.md

How it works
Claude Code automatically reads the CLAUDE.md file when it starts in any project folder. Every session begins with the same design context — it's like giving Claude a permanent brief about how to build your UI.

💡 Commit the CLAUDE.md file to your Git repo so your entire team benefits from the same design system instructions every time they use Claude Code.




STEP 4  Add the 21st.dev Magic MCP


What is 21st.dev Magic?
21st.dev Magic is like having v0.dev (Vercel's AI design tool) built directly into your terminal. It's an MCP (Model Context Protocol) server that lets Claude generate polished, production-ready UI components from natural language — just type "/ui create a hero section with gradient background" and it writes the files for you.

Step 4a — Get your free API key
Visit https://21st.dev/magic
Create a free account
Copy your API key from the dashboard

Step 4b — Add the MCP to Claude Code
Run this in your terminal:
claude mcp add @21st-dev/magic

Or add it manually to your Claude Code config file:
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "@21st-dev/magic": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@21st-dev/magic@latest"],
      "env": {
        "API_KEY": "your-21st-dev-api-key"
      }
    }
  }
}

How to use it
Inside Claude Code, describe the UI you want:

/ui create a modern navigation bar with responsive mobile menu
/ui build a pricing section with 3 tiers and toggle for monthly/annual
/ui make a hero section with a floating card and gradient background

💡 21st.dev generates components following your project's existing code style and structure. All generated code is fully editable TypeScript/React.


🔗 21st.dev Magic: https://21st.dev/magic



